A vector field is given by 
\begin_inset Formula \( \vec{F}(x,y,z)=x^{2}y\vec{i}+\left( \frac{x^{3}}{3}+x\right) \vec{j}+\vec{k} \)
\end_inset 

 .
\begin_deeper 
\layout Enumerate

[10 marks] Compute 
\begin_inset Formula \( \bigtriangledown \cdot \vec{F} \)
\end_inset 

 (the divergence).
 Show your work.
\newline 
Answer:
\begin_inset Formula \( \bigtriangledown \cdot \vec{F}=2xy \)
\end_inset 


\layout Enumerate

[10 marks] Compute 
\begin_inset Formula \( \bigtriangledown \times \vec{F} \)
\end_inset 

 (the curl).
 Show your work.
\newline 
Answer:
\begin_inset Formula \( \bigtriangledown \times \vec{F}=\vec{k} \)
\end_inset 


\layout Enumerate

[20 marks] Compute the line integral 
\begin_inset Formula \( \oint _{C}\vec{F}\cdot d\vec{r} \)
\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula \( C \)
\end_inset 

 is the unit circle centered at 
\begin_inset Formula \( 0 \)
\end_inset 

 on the plane (
\begin_inset Formula \( x^{2}+y^{2}=1 \)
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula \( z=0 \)
\end_inset 

) using Stoke's theorem.
 State any assumption you make in integrating.
\newline 
Answer: 
\begin_inset Formula \( \oint _{C}\vec{F}\cdot d\vec{r}=\int _{C}\bigtriangledown \times \vec{F}dA=\int _{C}dA=\pi  \)
\end_inset 

 assuming counter-clockwise integration.
