Series and sequences
\begin_deeper 
\layout Enumerate

[10 marks] Give an example of a monotone sequence that does not converge.
\newline 
Answer: 1,2,3,4...
\layout Enumerate

[10 marks] Does the series 
\begin_inset Formula \( \sum _{k=1}^{\infty }\frac{e^{k}}{\left( k^{2}\right) !} \)
\end_inset 

converges? Does it converge absolutely? Prove your result.
\newline 
Answer: Since 
\begin_inset Formula \( \lim _{k\rightarrow \infty }\left| \frac{e^{k+1}}{(k+1)^{2}!}\frac{k^{2}!}{e^{k}}\right| =\lim _{k\rightarrow \infty }\left| \frac{e}{(k+1)^{2}...(k^{2}+1)}\right| =0 \)
\end_inset 

 it converges by the ratio test.
 Since we used the ratio test, it must converge absolutely.
\layout Enumerate

[10 marks] Show that the series 
\begin_inset Formula \( \sum _{k=1}^{\infty }\frac{(-1)^{2}}{\sqrt{k}} \)
\end_inset 

converges.
\newline 
Answer: It is an alternating series.
 By AST it must converge since 
\begin_inset Formula \( 1/\sqrt{k} \)
\end_inset 

 decreases.
\layout Enumerate

[10 marks] A convergent series is absolutely convergent.
 Prove or give a counter-example.
\newline 
Answer: Counter-example 
\begin_inset Formula \( 1,-1/2,1/3,-1/4,... \)
\end_inset 

 is 
\begin_inset Formula \( \ln 2 \)
\end_inset 

 whereas 
\begin_inset Formula \( 1,1/2,1/3,1/4,... \)
\end_inset 

 doesn't converge.
\layout Enumerate

[10 marks] Let 
\begin_inset Formula \( S_{n}=\sum _{k=1}^{n}\frac{(-1)^{2}}{\sqrt{k}} \)
\end_inset 

and 
\begin_inset Formula \( L=\sum _{k=1}^{\infty }\frac{(-1)^{2}}{\sqrt{k}} \)
\end_inset 

, find 
\begin_inset Formula \( N \)
\end_inset 

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula \( \left| S_{N}-L\right| <\frac{1}{3} \)
\end_inset 

.
\newline 
Answer: Since it is an alternating series, we have 
\begin_inset Formula \( \left| S_{N}-L\right| <\frac{1}{\sqrt{N+1}} \)
\end_inset 

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula \( N=8 \)
\end_inset 

 is a good choice.
